    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 14 @ 2023/2024",
    "Question": {
      "content": "The potential difference between the terminals of a source when no current flows to an external circuit is called the",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "net voltage",
        "Battery voltage",
        "Electromotive force",
        "Equivalent voltage"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "Electromotive force"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<p>The electromotive force (EMF) is the potential difference across the terminals of a source when no current is flowing, representing the maximum voltage it can provide.</p>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electric Potential",
      "DC Circuits",
      "Electric Current",
      "Electromotive force"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 18 @ 2023/2024",
    "Question": {
      "content": "The induced e.m.f. in a coil of wire of many turns is equal to the rate of change of magnetic flux linking the coil. This is a statement of",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "Ampere's law",
        "Lenz's law",
        "Biot-Savart's law",
        "Faraday's law"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "Faraday's law"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<p>Faraday's law of electromagnetic induction states that the induced electromotive force (emf) in a coil is equal to the negative rate of change of magnetic flux through the coil, i.e.,\\(\\mathcal{E} = -\\frac{d\\Phi}{dt}\\).</p>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Faraday's Law of Induction",
      "Electromotive force",
      "Magnetic Fields",
      "Electromagnetism"
    ]
  }
